article.description: Chris Webber scored 11 of his 22 points in the final period, helping the Kings rally for a 92-88 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers that kept them perfect on their road trip.
article.headline: With dislocated finger, Webber a pain to Sixers

images.name: Webber_Chris 020313 inline
images.caption: Chris Webber scored 22 points and played some serious defense against the Sixers.

article.linkText: Webber points Kings past Sixers with dislocated finger
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Chris Webber doesn't know if he'll play the next two games. His teammates are glad he finished this one. Webber, playing with a dislocated right index finger, had 22 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Sacramento Kings to a 92-88 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Wednesday night. "It was bad," said Webber, who was hurt diving for a loose ball. "I don't know if I'll be able to play against New York and Toronto. What we did tonight is what Philly is known for, playing through injuries. That's what we're trying to be known for." Peja Stojakovic added 21 points and Mike Bibby had 12 as the Kings won their fourth straight and improved their NBA-best record to 46-17. Webber hurt his finger at the end of the first quarter, but returned midway through the second. The injury seemed to affect his shooting. He missed 11 of 13 shots at one point before scoring 11 in the fourth. "Some guys wouldn't have played the rest of the game," Stojakovic said of Webber. "We're playing together, helping each other, showing real character." Allen Iverson scored 32 points, Derrick Coleman added 20 and Dikembe Mutombo had 14 points and 17 rebounds for the Sixers, who had won four in a row. The defending Eastern Conference champions missed an opportunity to pull within five games of first-place New Jersey in the Atlantic Division. Coleman had to be restrained from going after Webber after the game. Both players got technicals with 32 seconds left. "He's from Detroit, man," said Webber, a fellow Michigan native who has known Coleman since he was 8. Sacramento took its first lead since early in the first, 75-74, on a 10-footer by Webber midway through the fourth. But Iverson answered with a jumper and Eric Snow made a free throw to give the Sixers a 77-75 lead. The teams traded leads until Bibby's jumper made it 85-84 with 2:09 left. After a turnover by Iverson, Vlade Divac scored on a putback and Webber made a free throw for an 88-84 lead. Snow hit two free throws to cut it to 88-86 with 14.2 seconds left, but Stojakovic and Bobby Jackson iced it with four free throws in the final 11 seconds. "I don't care about moral victories," said Iverson, who was 7-for-10 in the first quarter, but missed 15 of his last 21 shots. "We're a better team than those guys. We had it and gave it away." The Sixers took a 35-34 lead early in the second following an 11-2 run, ignited by a 3-pointer from Harpring as the shot clock expired. A short jumper by Corie Blount gave Philadelphia its biggest lead, 50-36, with 3:28 left in the first half. But the Kings scored seven straight points and trailed 52-45 at halftime. "With 2½ minutes left, we had control of the game, but we took some bad shots and made some bad turnovers," Sixers coach Larry Brown said.

Game notes
The Kings beat the Sixers 100-79 at the First Union Center last season, but Iverson was just returning from an injury. They also beat the Sixers earlier this season in Sacramento, 94-84, without Webber and Doug Christie. ... Coleman got a flagrant foul on Mike Bibby midway through the first quarter. The Sixers were called for three flagrant fouls Tuesday night against the Knicks, including two on Mutombo. ... It was Stojakovic's first game in Philadelphia since winning the 3-point shootout last month during All-Star weekend. ... Coleman, in his second game back after missing three games with a hyperextended left knee, also scored 20 points in Philadelphia's 104-96 comeback victory at New York on Tuesday night. ... The Sixers, who led by five after three quarters, are 28-5 when taking a lead into the fourth. ... Sacramento tied a season-low with one 3-pointer.
